# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ballerina-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] The project began in 2015 by architects from WSO2 as a code-based alternative to the configuration-based integration tools such as enterprise application integration (EAI), enterprise service bus (ESB), and workflow products.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] It has various constructs for cloud-native development including support for various data formats and protocols, reliability, distributed transactions, application programming interfaces (APIs), and event streams.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] Ballerina was first publicly announced in 2017 and version 1.0 was released on September 10, 2019.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] Ballerina is a general-purpose language with a familiar syntax along with a direct graphical representation of the code in the form of sequence diagrams.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] It has fundamental abstractions designed to make integration problems easier to program.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] Ballerina was designed by WSO2 to improve productivity for application developers that have to work with distributed computing.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] It is easy to write and modify and is suitable for application programmers.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] The designers, who provided enterprise integration products for over 10 years, used their knowledge of the industry when designing the language, says WSO2 director and Ballerina founder James Clark.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] To execute the above program, place the source code in a `.bal` file and provide the path of the file to the `bal run` command.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] Services are executed in the same manner, except they don't terminate like regular programs do.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] Once the service is up and running, one can use an HTTP client to invoke the service.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] The generated sequence diagram is a canonical representation of the source code.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] The two representations can be used interchangeably.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] The diagram support is provided through the Ballerina VS Code plugin.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] The following are a couple of such generated sequence diagrams, compared with its associated code.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] The language provides support for working with JSON values.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] Docker and Kubernetes artifacts required for deploying the code to the cloud can be generated when building the code.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] Values required for these artifacts are derived from the code.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] Additionally, one can override these values as well using the `Cloud.toml` file.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] To enable generation of the cloud artifacts, the users can use the `cloud` build option in the `Ballerina.toml` file.
[src:ballerina-lang/ballerina-programming-language] Use `docker` to generate just the Docker image and the Dockerfile and use `k8s` to generate Kubernetes artifacts as well.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:ballerina-lang/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] This is a property of a system—whether a program, computer, or a network—where there is a separate execution point or "thread of control" for each process.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] A *concurrent system* is one where a computation can advance without waiting for all other computations to complete.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing is a form of modular programming.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] In its paradigm an overall computation is factored into subcomputations that may be executed concurrently.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Pioneers in the field of concurrent computing include Edsger Dijkstra, Per Brinch Hansen, and C.A.R.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] The concept of concurrent computing is frequently confused with the related but distinct concept of parallel computing, although both can be described as "multiple processes executing *during the same period of time*".
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] By contrast, concurrent computing consists of process *lifetimes* overlapping, but execution does not happen at the same instant.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] The goal here is to model processes that happen concurrently, like multiple clients accessing a server at the same time.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Structuring software systems as composed of multiple concurrent, communicating parts can be useful for tackling complexity, regardless of whether the parts can be executed in parallel.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] In this way, multiple processes are part-way through execution at a single instant, but only one process is being executed at that instant.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computations *may* be executed in parallel, for example, by assigning each process to a separate processor or processor core, or distributing a computation across a network.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] The exact timing of when tasks in a concurrent system are executed depends on the scheduling, and tasks need not always be executed concurrently.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] The word "sequential" is used as an antonym for both "concurrent" and "parallel"; when these are explicitly distinguished, *concurrent/sequential* and *parallel/serial* are used as opposing pairs.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] A schedule in which tasks execute one at a time (serially, no parallelism), without interleaving (sequentially, no concurrency: no task begins until the prior task ends) is called a *serial schedule*.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] A set of tasks that can be scheduled serially is *serializable*, which simplifies concurrency control.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] The main challenge in designing concurrent programs is concurrency control: ensuring the correct sequencing of the interactions or communications between different computational executions, and coordinating access to resources that are shared among executions.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Potential problems include race conditions, deadlocks, and resource starvation.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Suppose `balance = 500`, and two concurrent *threads* make the calls `withdraw(300)` and `withdraw(350)`.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] If line 3 in both operations executes before line 5 both operations will find that `balance >= withdrawal` evaluates to `true`, and execution will proceed to subtracting the withdrawal amount.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] However, since both processes perform their withdrawals, the total amount withdrawn will end up being more than the original balance.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] These sorts of problems with shared resources benefit from the use of concurrency control, or non-blocking algorithms.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Introduced in 1962, Petri nets were an early attempt to codify the rules of concurrent execution.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Dataflow theory later built upon these, and Dataflow architectures were created to physically implement the ideas of dataflow theory.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Beginning in the late 1970s, process calculi such as Calculus of Communicating Systems (CCS) and Communicating Sequential Processes (CSP) were developed to permit algebraic reasoning about systems composed of interacting components.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] The π-calculus added the capability for reasoning about dynamic topologies.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Input/output automata were introduced in 1987.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Logics such as Lamport's TLA+, and mathematical models such as traces and Actor event diagrams, have also been developed to describe the behavior of concurrent systems.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Software transactional memory borrows from database theory the concept of atomic transactions and applies them to memory accesses.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages and multiprocessor programs must have a consistency model (also known as a memory model).
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] The consistency model defines rules for how operations on computer memory occur and how results are produced.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] One of the first consistency models was Leslie Lamport's sequential consistency model.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Sequential consistency is the property of a program that its execution produces the same results as a sequential program.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Specifically, a program is sequentially consistent if "the results of any execution is the same as if the operations of all the processors were executed in some sequential order, and the operations of each individual processor appear in this sequence in the order specified by its program".
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] A number of different methods can be used to implement concurrent programs, such as implementing each computational execution as an operating system process, or implementing the computational processes as a set of threads within a single operating system process.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] In some concurrent computing systems, communication between the concurrent components is hidden from the programmer (e.g., by using futures), while in others it must be handled explicitly.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] The exchange of messages may be carried out asynchronously, or may use a synchronous "rendezvous" style in which the sender blocks until the message is received.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Asynchronous message passing may be reliable or unreliable (sometimes referred to as "send and pray").
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Message-passing concurrency tends to be far easier to reason about than shared-memory concurrency, and is typically considered a more robust form of concurrent programming.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Shared memory and message passing concurrency have different performance characteristics.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Typically (although not always), the per-process memory overhead and task switching overhead is lower in a message passing system, but the overhead of message passing is greater than for a procedure call.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] These differences are often overwhelmed by other performance factors.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing developed out of earlier work on railroads and telegraphy, from the 19th and early 20th century, and some terms date to this period, such as semaphores.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] These arose to address the question of how to handle multiple trains on the same railroad system (avoiding collisions and maximizing efficiency) and how to handle multiple transmissions over a given set of wires (improving efficiency), such as via time-division multiplexing (1870s).
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] The academic study of concurrent algorithms started in the 1960s, with Dijkstra (1965) credited with being the first paper in this field, identifying and solving mutual exclusion.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Concurrency is pervasive in computing, occurring from low-level hardware on a single chip to worldwide networks.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] At the network level, networked systems are generally concurrent by their nature, as they consist of separate devices.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages are programming languages that use language constructs for concurrency.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] These constructs may involve multi-threading, support for distributed computing, message passing, shared resources (including shared memory) or futures and promises.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Such languages are sometimes described as *concurrency-oriented languages* or *concurrency-oriented programming languages* (COPL).
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Today, the most commonly used programming languages that have specific constructs for concurrency are Java and C#.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Both of these languages fundamentally use a shared-memory concurrency model, with locking provided by monitors (although message-passing models can and have been implemented on top of the underlying shared-memory model).
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Of the languages that use a message-passing concurrency model, Erlang was probably the most widely used in industry as of 2010.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Many concurrent programming languages have been developed more as research languages (e.g., Pict) rather than as languages for production use.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] However, languages such as Erlang, Limbo, and occam have seen industrial use at various times in the last 20 years.
[src:ballerina-lang/concurrent-computing] Many other languages provide support for concurrency in the form of libraries, at levels roughly comparable with the above list.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] This guide introduces the Ballerina language to help you get started with basics that are common to all C-Family programming languages.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina is a modern programming language focused on building applications for the cloud era.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It has a familiar syntax resembling the C-family of languages such as C/C++, C#, Java, and JavaScript.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It brings in many powerful concepts from existing programming languages and some unconventional abstraction mechanisms to make application development for the cloud more intuitive and less strenuous.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] This guide presents the subset of the Ballerina language that is common to most modern programming languages.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It covers the baseline features such as data types, control flow, and error handling, which should be very familiar to most programmers.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] These features are the foundation for some of the more distinctive features of Ballerina.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina programs consist of modules and each module consists of one or more *`.bal`* files.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The most important thing that a module does is define named functions.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `import` keyword is used to bind predefined library modules to the module prefix.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina modules have two-part names represented by an organization name and a module name.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In this case, the organization is **`ballerina`** and the module is **`io`**.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The bound identifier that refers to this library module is set to the module name **`io`**.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] To override the default identifier binding for the module, you can use the `as` keyword as follows: *`import ballerina/io as oi`*.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Module hierarchies follow the `/` and `.` notations.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] For example, *`org/x.y.z`* represents a hierarchical module name.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `z:f` notation points to a symbol `f` (e.g., a function) defined within the module `x.y.z`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `main` function is the program entry point and the `public` keyword makes this function visible outside the module.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] This `main` function calls the `println()` function defined in the `ballerina/io` module.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Every statement in Ballerina code must terminate with a semicolon.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Modules and functions can declare variables.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina defines several built-in types such as integers, floating point numbers, strings, and booleans.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In Ballerina, variable assignments are statements and not expressions.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Like all high-level programming languages, Ballerina supports functions.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] A function definition in Ballerina has a familiar syntax that includes parameters and a return type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In the above code example, you see the definition for the **`add`** function.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It accepts two parameters of type `int`, **`x`**, and **`y`**.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `returns` keyword specifies the type of return value.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The function performs a simple addition operation and stores the result in another variable **`sum`** of type `int`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `return` statement returns the value assigned to **`sum`**.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The overall syntax is more or less C-like.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Comments start with `//` and end at the end of the line.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Module definitions/declarations and statements use braces or terminate with a semicolon.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can also use Unicode characters in identifiers.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Unicode literals can be defined using the `\u{H}` syntax to represent Unicode code points in the hex format.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Keywords such as `int`, `function`, and `string` are reserved keywords in Ballerina.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can use them as identifiers by prefixing them with a single quote.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina defines an integer data type of a 64-bit signed representation.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `int` keyword is used to declare an integer.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Integer literals can be declared either in decimal or hexadecimal format.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The integer data type supports all the basic arithmetic operators: `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, and `%`, the comparison operators: `==`, `!=`, `<`, `>`, `<=`, and `>=` as well as the compound assignment operators: `+=` and `-=`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The operator precedence rules are exactly as per C.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] However, there are a couple of notable deviations in Ballerina.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Firstly, increment and decrement operators (i.e., `++` and `--`) are not supported.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Moreover, integer overflow results in a runtime error unlike in C where it rolls over.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In Ballerina, floating point numbers have an IEEE 64-bit binary representation similar to `double` in Java.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Variables of the `float` type are declared with the `float` keyword and they support all operations similar to integers except bitwise operators.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] However, they cannot be implicitly converted to or from integers.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can use the `<T>` notation for explicit conversion.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In Ballerina, `NaN`, the IEEE defined terminology for Not a Number is equal to itself.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Therefore, the `==` operator on two `NaN`s will return `true`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] For floating point types, the `==` and `!=` operators test for the same value and do not test for numerical equivalence as per the IEEE convention.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The boolean type has only two values: `true` and `false`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina supports the logical operators, `!`, `||`, and `&&` with boolean values.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `||` and `&&` operators support the same short-circuit behavior as in C.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Implicit conversion between boolean and integer is not supported.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] If-else statements and all compound statements in Ballerina require curly braces.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] However, the parenthesis before the curly braces are optional.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It has a special significance in Ballerina as it denotes the equivalent of what is known as a null value in other C-family languages.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] If you want to declare a variable or a value of type nil, here is how it is done.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The keyword `int` is followed by a `?` notation.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It means that **`v`** can take an integer value or can be nil.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It is initialized to nil, which is denoted by `()`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Types do not allow their values to be set as nil implicitly.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] There is also no implicit conversion to boolean.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `==` and `!=` comparison operators operate on a value to test whether the value is nil.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Similarly, you can also use the Elvis operator like *`x ?: y`* that returns **`x`** if it is not nil or **`y`** otherwise.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Leaving off the return type of a function is the same as defining nil as the return type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Moreover, falling off the end of a function or `return` by itself is equivalent to `return ()`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Strings are immutable sequences of zero or more Unicode characters.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] To define a variable of type `string`, you use the `string` keyword in Ballerina.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] String literals are enclosed in double quotes and support the usual C-style escape sequences as well as numeric escape characters for Unicode code points.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `string` type supports the usual operators.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `==` operator checks for the same characters.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The comparison operators (i.e., `<`, `<=`, `=>`, and `>`) work by comparing code points.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `+` operator is used for concatenation.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The member access expression (e.g., `s[i]`) on a string value points to the character at index `i` of the string.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The index positions on values of the `string` type start with zero.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina does not support the notion of a separate character type like in C.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Instead, a character is considered a string of length one.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina defines lang libraries to provide fundamental operations on built-in datatypes.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] For example, you can perform standard operations such as getting a substring or finding the length of the string on values of the `string` type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `substring()` and `length()` functions are `string` lang library functions called using the convenient method call syntax.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] However, the functions are called on variables/values of the `string` type rather than objects.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] A lang library **`ballerina/lang.T`** is defined for each built-in type **`T`**.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina automatically imports these lang libraries and pre-declares a prefix **`T`**, which you can use to access the constructs of the module.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Therefore, in the case of the above code example, you can also find the length of the string value referring to the **`length()`** function as **`string:length()`** and using the function call syntax.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The lang library can also be imported explicitly as **`import ballerina/lang.'string`**.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Arrays are ordered data structures consisting of values of the same type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can index the individual elements of this array using the `v[i]` notation.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] So the second element of **`v`** can be accessed as *`v[1]`*.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina supports ordering based on a lexicographical ordering of members.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `==` and `!=` comparison operators perform a deep comparison of two arrays based on the members and their order instead of the memory location.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Langlib functions for arrays are available to perform operations such as finding the length of an array.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] A `foreach` statement iterates over an array by binding a variable to each array member at every loop iteration.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In this code example, the **`x`** variable of the `float` type is bound to each element of the **`v`** array.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Similarly, it also works with the `string` type by iterating over each character in the string.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can also construct the `foreach` statement using a range expression such as `..<`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The above statement sets the **`i`** variable of the `int` type to a sequence of linearly incrementing numbers that range from zero to the length of the array **`v`**.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Therefore, the `foreach` statement iterates over the length of the array and increments **`i`** during each iteration.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `while` loop in Ballerina behaves exactly like in C.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In this example, the `while` loop is checking for a boolean condition to check for the end of the linked list **`ll`**.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `while` statement also supports the usual `break` and `continue` statements.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Binary data is represented by an array of bytes.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] An array of bytes can also be represented in the source code using base-64 or base-16 literal formats.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `byte` type represents a number between `0` and `0xFF`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can define a variable of the `byte` type with the `byte` keyword.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In Ballerina, `byte` is a subtype of the integer type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Therefore, it supports all the bitwise operators available on integers.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Some of these operators produce a value that belongs to the integer type, and some operators like the `&` operator produce a value that belongs to the `byte` type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] A map is an associative structure of multiple string values as keys and their values.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The syntax to define a map is very similar to JSON.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Maps are mutable, and *`m["x"]`* will return the integer value stored against *`x`* as the key, or nil if the key is not present.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] When used in a `foreach` loop, it will iterate over all the values of the map.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can also use lang library functions such as *`get(k)`* to get the value mapped to the string key *`k`*, or *`keys( )`* to return an array containing all the key strings of the map.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can perform a deep comparison by using the `==` and `!=` comparison operators on a map.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Two maps are equal if they have the same set of keys and the values for each key are equal.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina allows you to define a name for a type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can create user-defined type identifiers for the built-in types supported by the language.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] This is similar to the typedef concept in C, where the identifier **`MapArray`** acts as an alias for the actual type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] A record is a collection of fields of a specific type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] With record types, you have control over what your keys are.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The above code defines a record **`r`** with two integer fields **`x`** and **`y`**, and initializes their values to 1 and 2, respectively.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Subsequently, you can use the **`Coord`** record to declare a variable and set or access its field values.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Rules for record comparison are the same as those for maps.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In Ballerina, the data types are defined in terms of a set of values.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] These values can be part of a finite set or an infinite set.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] For example, the `int` type has a finite set consisting of values within the range of 64-bit signed numbers.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `string` type is an infinite set that contains sequences of any number or order of characters.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In this way, Ballerina partitions the universe of all values into the basic types it supports such as nil, boolean, integer, floating point, and string.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Values of these basic types are immutable, and each value belongs to exactly one basic type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] There is also a concept of semantic subtyping, which means a subset of the values of the basic types.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] For example, the `byte` type is a subset of integer as it allows only a subset of values that are a part of the integer value set.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Additionally, Ballerina allows you to define your own types, such as arrays, maps, and records, which are mutable.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina's type system allows you to define custom types based on the combination of two or more types.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] A union is, therefore, a superset of that combination.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] A variable of type `T?` can hold a value of type `T` or nil as explained in the section on the Nil type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Similarly, you can define a variable that holds an integer or a string.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can create a union of multiple types using the `|` symbol in the type definition.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Therefore, in the above example, **`flexType`** can hold an integer value as well as a string value, and the Ballerina compiler won't complain.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can also apply the concept of unions to structured data types like records.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] So it is possible to have a union of a record type containing fields of the `string` type and the basic `string` type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] At runtime, you can define the business logic by checking the currently held value of the union-typed variable using the `is` operator.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In this way, the `is` operator in a condition causes the declared type to be narrowed.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina does not support the notion of exceptions.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Instead, errors are handled as part of the normal control flow.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Errors are first-class citizens in Ballerina.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina supports a few mechanisms that are centered around an `error` type to handle errors.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina programs can pass around error values similar to values of any other type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Functions report errors by returning error values.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In the above code example, the function **`parse()`** returns either an integer or an error.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] At the point of returning the error, the error constructor *`error("not a digit")`* is called.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In case a function is expected to explicitly return only error values, a return type of `error?` is used.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ignoring an error also has to be done explicitly.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] An error value includes a string message and the stack trace from the point where *`error(...)`* is called.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] When an error is reported from a function, it is passed up to its caller.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ultimately it is handled at the `main` function, which can return it.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Alternatively, you can use the `is` operator to check for the error type as part of the regular control flow to make a decision.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In the above code example, the function defines a local variable **`ret`** to hold the value returned by the **`string:fromBytes()`** function.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The **`ret`** variable is of a union type of the `string` and `error` types.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Therefore to ascertain the actual type, `is` operator is used.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Instead of using the `is` operator within the regular conditional flow to check for errors, Ballerina supports the `check` keyword as a shorthand method.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Error handling and return statements become much more concise when using the `check` keyword.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In this case, the expression following the `check` keyword (`string:fromBytes(bytes)`) is evaluated and the **`intFromBytes`** function returns immediately if the **`string:fromBytes()`** function returns an error.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina also allows fine-grained error detection based on error subtypes.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Error subtypes can be defined using the distinct keyword.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Now, you can use the defined subtype in an error constructor to create error values of that type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can use the `is` operator to distinguish between the distinct subtypes.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In Ballerina, there is a distinction between normal and abnormal errors.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Normal errors are the ones that you typically handle as part of the usual business logic and are under your control.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] But some errors are not under the control of the programmer.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Things such as bugs in library code or out of memory errors fall under this category.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Normal errors are handled by returning values of the `error` type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Abnormal errors are handled using the `panic` statement.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] A panic statement results in immediate program termination and has an associated error value.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina also has an `any` type, which means any value except an error value.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] A variable of type `any` can be cast to a specific type using the type cast expression (`<T>x`).
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can also use the `is` operator to test the type of the actual value held by the variable.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina does not allow silently ignoring return values of functions unless they return nil.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] To ignore the return value, you can assign it to `_`, which acts as an implicitly declared variable of any type that cannot be referenced.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] When a function's return type includes an `error` type, it has to be handled explicitly.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Otherwise, the `checkpanic` keyword can be used but it panics on error rather than returning.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina's type system follows a structured type system based on the set of values that belongs to a type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] For example, the integer type allows a set of values.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Similarly, the `any` type also allows a set of values, including the subset of values that belong to the integer type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Therefore, you can have an array of the integer type that is assigned to an array of the `any` type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] This is perfectly valid in Ballerina because the set of values allowed by an array of the integer type is a subset of the values allowed by an array of the `any` type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] So this way, you can have some flexibility in allowing fixed inherent type substitution based on the set of values.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina's static type checking ensures that the result of a read operation on the array **`av`** will be consistent with static type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] However, writing may result in an error because the inherent type of the `iv` array is array of integers.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] As a result, the code below will lead to a runtime error since it is trying to mutate the array to a type other than the inherent type (`int[]`).
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] This is covariance, which means that a write to a mutable structure may result in a runtime error.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Apart from arrays, maps and records are the other data structures with an inherent type that constrains mutation.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina provides another basic type which is the object type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Object types bundle together code and data.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Objects are initialized based on a class defined within a module.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In the above code example, the function **`demoMyClass()`** uses the `new` expression to create an object **`x`** using the **`MyClass`** class that is defined in module `m`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can use the `.` notation to call the object's methods or access its fields.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina supports the concept of a class which is a structured type containing data and behavior.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The **`init`** method is the constructor for this class, and the keyword `self` is used to access the object.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It also uses the standard access specifiers, `private` and `public`, which translate to accessibility within the class definition and outside of it.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The **`init()`** method of a class can have a return type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The return type must be a subtype of the union of `error` and `nil`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] If the *`init()`* call returns normally, the newly constructed object is returned.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Otherwise, the `new` expression returns the error value.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The return type of the **`init()`** method is nil if a return type is not explicitly specified.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It also means that the `init` method will never return an error.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In Ballerina, the identity of an object is determined by the memory location in which the object resides at runtime.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] To check the identity, you can use the `===` and `!==` equality expressions.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In the above code example, both **`obj1`** and **`obj2`** are **`MyClass`** objects.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] *`obj1 === obj1`* returns true as both operands of the operation refer to the same memory location.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Similarly, *`obj1 === obj2`* returns false since they refer to different memory locations.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `==` operator is used to check for contents of a structure type like arrays.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In the above code example, the first operation results in true as both the arrays have exactly the same content.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] However, the second operation is false because it is using the `===` operator to check for memory locations, and the two inline arrays point to different memory locations, even though their contents are the same.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In the case of floating point numbers, IEEE defines -0.0 and +0.0 as the same.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Therefore applying `==` to compare -0.0 and +0.0 would return `true`, whereas *`-0.0 === +0.0`* would always be `false` as they are not identical.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Constants are defined using the `const` keyword and are immutable singleton types having a value known at compile time.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Apart from `const`, there is also support for `final`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Variables defined with the `final` keyword cannot be reassigned to after being initialized.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] This is also applicable for class fields.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina supports the notion of enumerations which is a shorthand way for expressing unions of string constants.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can also have an enumeration where members define associated string values explicitly.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The `match` statement is like the switch case statement in C, but it is more flexible.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can use it to match values of different types.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The match statement defines multiple clause statement blocks with the `=>` operator.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The left-hand side of the `=>` operator in each clause is the pattern for the value match.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It can contain literals or identifiers referring to constants.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It can also contain multiple patterns specified using `|`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Additionally, `_` can be used to match any value that is not an error.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In the above example, the match statement uses the value held by **`v`** and matches it against six match clauses having distinct patterns.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] During execution, the patterns will be evaluated in order, using the equality expression (`==`) to test the pattern match, and the matched clause's statement block will be executed.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Type inference allows the program to infer the actual data type of variables.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] This feature is a convenient way to use a generic type for a local variable and helps avoid repeated type declarations.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In this code example, the keyword `var` is used to declare the variable **`x`**.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It means that the variable's actual type will be inferred from the type of the expression used to initialize it.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] This is especially useful in a `foreach` loop to declare the local variable for iterating over a collection, like arrays.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In this code example, the type of variable **`s`** is inferred to be of type `string`, from the type of **`sv`**, which is an array of type `string`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Here the variable **`x`** is declared with `var` and the type is inferred as **`MyClass`**.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The opposite syntax is also valid, wherein the variable **`x`** is defined with the **`MyClass`** type and is initialized with `new`.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Type inference is applicable for variables in local scopes.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Therefore `var` should be used sparingly for variables used within a very limited scope, like in a `foreach` loop.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Overusing it makes the code harder to understand.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina defines functions also as values, and they work as closures.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In the above example, the variable **`isOdd`** defines an anonymous function.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] **`IntFilter`** is a function type that accepts a function with an `int` argument and returns a `boolean` value.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] And later on, the **`isEven`** function, with a matching signature, is assigned to a variable of this type.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] These function values can be passed around as arguments.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] For example, the lang library for arrays defines a function **`filter(f)`** which accepts a function type **`f`** to perform specific filtering operations on arrays.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The **`filter()`** function takes the function value as a parameter, which is **`isEven`**, assigned to **`f`**.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Therefore, passing it as the argument results in `filter()` returning an array of even numbers.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Instead of passing a function variable, you can also pass anonymous functions as an argument.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] As shown for the array **`oddNums`**, the type of parameter **`n`** is inferred from the array with which the **`filter()`** function is used.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina also supports asynchronous function calls.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The use of the `start` keyword before the function call makes it asynchronous.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Each asynchronous call runs on a separate logical thread, also known as strand, that is cooperatively multitasked by default.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The result of this invocation is returned as a future.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] It is a separate basic type that has an attached type *`T`* as *`future<T>`*.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can then wait for the result with the `wait` keyword.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Waiting on a *`future<T>`* returns *`T|error`*.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Waiting on the same future more than once returns an error value.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Instead of waiting for each future separately, you can also do the following.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In case you want to terminate the `future`, you can do *`f.cancel( )`*.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Ballerina supports a structured way to document code.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Documentation lines start with `#` and contain structured documentation in Markdown format.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The above code example adds documentation to describe the parameters and the return type of the **`add()`** function.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] This is Ballerina-flavoured Markdown (BFM) which makes it convenient to generate pretty documentation using one of the platform tools.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] Annotations are defined using the `@` notation followed by a tag.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] This is a way of attaching metadata to the code.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] In the above code example, the *`@display`* annotation is attached to the function **`transform()`**, and the *`@strand`* annotation applies to the keyword `start`, calling the function **`foo()`** asynchronously.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] These annotations use mapping constructor expressions, which is one of the ways to define them.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] The annotations shown above use unprefixed tags and refer to standard platform-defined annotations.
[src:ballerina-lang/language-basics] You can also have prefixed tags for user-defined annotations declared in modules.
